cal philosophy are various, with some friendlier to religious belief than others, almost all place constraints on the philosophic and political role of revelation. Mainstream secular political theorists do not entirely disregard religion. But to the extent that they pay attention, their treatment of religious belief is seen more as a political or philosophic problem to be addressed rather than as a positive body of thought from which we might derive important insights about the nature of politics and the truth of the human condition.In a one-of-a-kind collection, DeHart and Holloway bring together leading scholars from various fields, including political science, philosophy, and theology, to challenge the prevailing orthodoxy and to demonstrate the role that religion can and does play in political life. Contributing authors include such important thinkers as Peter Augustine Lawler, Robert C. Koons, J. Budziszewski, Francis J. Beckwith, and James Stoner.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aReligion and politics. 0aRevelation. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aReligious Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  areligious belief and philosophy, mainstream secular political theorists, religion in public life.1 aBeckwith, Francis J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradizza, Luigi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudziszewski, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeHart, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDehart, Paul R ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock, Ralph C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aH